 So why not? 

00:01:00.480 --> 00:01:03.239
 Well, first, let's look at the technical details. 

00:01:03.239 --> 00:01:06.590
 It all depends on who holds the keys. 

00:01:06.590 --> 00:01:08.220
 Modern encryption uses complicated mathematics 

00:01:08.220 --> 00:01:10.960
 it is easy for a computer to calculate one way, 

00:01:10.960 --> 00:01:13.270
 but almost impossible for it, the other way. 

00:01:13.270 --> 00:01:14.430
 A really simple example: 

00:01:14.430 --> 00:01:18.689
 If I ask you to multiply two prime numbers, like 13 × 17, 

00:01:18.689 --> 00:01:21.490
 You can do this by just pressing a few keys on your calculator. 

00:01:21.490 --> 00:01:23.220
 And because they were prime numbers, 

00:01:23.220 --> 00:01:28.340
 We know this is the only way to get 221 by multiplying two whole numbers together. 

00:01:28.340 --> 00:01:31.860
 except 221 times 1, and it's not quite useful. 

00:01:31.860 --> 00:01:36.470
 But if I ask you, "Which two prime numbers should be multiplied to get 161?" 

00:01:36.470 --> 00:01:38.160
 There is no way to find out quickly. 

00:01:38.160 --> 00:01:40.079
 There are a few shortcuts you can take, 

00:01:40.079 --> 00:01:43.079
 But it is still basically a brute-force approach. 

00:01:43.079 --> 00:01:45.500
 Now imagine you're not trying to calculate for 161, 

00:01:45.500 --> 00:01:48.250
 but instead something like this ... 

00:01:48.250 --> 00:01:50.070
 you begin to see the scale of the problem. 

00:01:50.070 --> 00:01:51.900
 And that's just a simple example, 

00:01:51.900 --> 00:01:55.600
 Modern cryptography uses far more complicated one-way operations. 

00:01:55.600 --> 00:02:00.340
 The important thing is that you can get a computer to do maths that are single-way, 

00:02:00.340 --> 00:02:05.030
 but could take longer than the lifetime of the universe to brute-force back. 

00:02:05.030 --> 00:02:08.110
 The result is that you can have two keys: two huge numbers. 

00:02:08.110 --> 00:02:09.410
 One public, one private. 

00:02:09.410 --> 00:02:12.090
 You send your public key to the world. 

00:02:12.090 --> 00:02:13.810
 Anyone can encrypt a message with it; 

00:02:13.810 --> 00:02:16.670
 the message is converted to what looks like random noise. 

00:02:16.670 --> 00:02:19.850
 Even the same public key cannot convert it back. 

00:02:19.850 --> 00:02:22.020
 But you can take the noise and use your private key 

00:02:22.020 --> 00:02:23.920
 - and only your private key - 

00:02:23.920 --> 00:02:24.920
 to decrypt it. 

00:02:24.920 --> 00:02:27.620
 When you want to send a message back, you use their public key, 

00:02:27.620 --> 00:02:29.560
 and they use their private key to decrypt it. 

00:02:29.560 --> 00:02:34.760
 And the beautiful part of this: there is no need to exchange keys in advance, 

00:02:34.760 --> 00:02:38.230
 You don't have to work out old-school disposable pads, or anything like that. 

00:02:38.230 --> 00:02:41.220
 You can send your public key to the internet for anyone to see. 

00:02:41.220 --> 00:02:43.750
 As long as you keep the private key secret, 

00:02:43.750 --> 00:02:44.950
 no one else can read your messages. 

00:02:44.950 --> 00:02:50.050
 It's a system that has been tested under incredibly harsh conditions for decades. 

00:02:50.050 --> 00:02:52.160
 It works. 

00:02:52.160 --> 00:02:54.030
 The chin knows it's really unfriendly to use. 

00:02:54.030 --> 00:02:57.310
 It's hard enough to get someone to join a new bedding service as it is, 

