 not to talk about getting their friends along. 

00:02:59.160 --> 00:03:01.460
 Now you have to generate strange key hallucinations too? 

00:03:01.460 --> 00:03:04.100
 And if you lose your phone or otherwise forget the key, 

00:03:04.100 --> 00:03:06.350
 or your hard drive breaks down and you are without a backup, 

00:03:06.350 --> 00:03:10.230
 are all your messages gone, lost as random noise forever. 

00:03:10.230 --> 00:03:13.220
 E-mail that works this way has been around for decades 

00:03:13.220 --> 00:03:16.060
 But it is too complicated and it is too unfriendly for most people. 

00:03:16.060 --> 00:03:18.480
 The security was not worth the effort. 

00:03:18.480 --> 00:03:19.810
 So instead, let web mail services, 

00:03:19.810 --> 00:03:22.370
 along with Facebook, Twitter, and everyone else, 

00:03:22.370 --> 00:03:23.370
 Don't worry about it. 

00:03:23.370 --> 00:03:25.100
 Previously, they were mostly unencrypted, 

00:03:25.100 --> 00:03:27.180
 but quickly realized that was a bad idea - 

00:03:27.180 --> 00:03:29.300
 so now they use regular web encryption, 

00:03:29.300 --> 00:03:30.920
 the padlock on your browser, 

00:03:30.920 --> 00:03:32.750
 to make sure nobody on your network can see 

00:03:32.750 --> 00:03:36.030
 your password or messages when they are underway 

00:03:36.030 --> 00:03:38.850
 And that is the threat most people care about. 

00:03:38.850 --> 00:03:41.910
 But they have the contents of the plain text messages, 

00:03:41.910 --> 00:03:43.040
 or something close to it, 

00:03:43.040 --> 00:03:45.550
 And these companies can give it back to you whenever you want. 

00:03:45.550 --> 00:03:48.700
 Which means that when a government comes with a warrant, 

00:03:48.700 --> 00:03:51.100
 companies can also provide the messages to them. 

00:03:51.100 --> 00:03:52.640
 And that was fine, right? 

00:03:52.640 --> 00:03:53.640
 This was reasonable. 

00:03:53.640 --> 00:03:57.230
 This was an acceptable compromise between security and ease of use. 

