 Even theoretically, should be able to access messages that people sent. 

00:04:18.400 --> 00:04:23.050
 The result is WhatsApp, and iMessage, and the many smaller apps like them. 

00:04:23.050 --> 00:04:25.690
 They have "end-to-end encryption". 

00:04:25.690 --> 00:04:29.680
 Your phone automatically generates a public and private key for you. 

00:04:29.680 --> 00:04:32.050
 It exchanges public keys behind the scenes, 

00:04:32.050 --> 00:04:33.650
 while writing your first message to someone 

00:04:33.650 --> 00:04:35.190
 and everything is encrypted. 

00:04:35.190 --> 00:04:36.190
 And all of it automatically! 

00:04:36.190 --> 00:04:39.010
 But WhatsApp and iMessage are not open source, 

00:04:39.010 --> 00:04:40.940
 so hypothetically they could steal your private key too 

00:04:40.940 --> 00:04:43.750
 or quietly issue a fake one to a person and sit in the middle listening, 

00:04:43.750 --> 00:04:45.890
 But in practice people would notice. 

00:04:45.890 --> 00:04:49.530
 There are certainly small loopholes that could work under special circumstances 

